title: For Sale/Trade:  Beautiful Russian AK74 wood furniture
postcontent: You think shooting an AK-47 style rifle is cheap? You need to research the AK-74 because it's about half the price per bullet right now. About $0.30 a round. And when people pull their head out of their @*$ and stop trying to scam you for ammo even though the ban is NOT going through, it'll be rediculously cheap. Up for sale or maybe trade, if you have something good, is a real AK74. Not an illegal bulgarian or romanian copy. The Izhmash factory in Russia makes these Saigas as sporting rifles. They are often converted to full Kalashnikov. Mine is really converted, not like the lazy ones who just convert the butstock and pistol grip and call it a day... Instead of being lazy and slapping on a rail system (because it's cheap and easy) I fitted a gas tube with upper handguard retainers, lower handguard retainer, AK74 furninture (which I refinished myself) including pistol grip, buttstock, and upper and lower handguards. Also, my saiga has the AK74 front sight with bayonet lug and an AKS-74U muzzle break. It doesn't get any better than this, not your WASR, not your bulgy copies, this is a russian AK74 in all respects. After fitting the gas tube I op checked the rifle with two 40 round magazines in about 10 seconds (including reload :)) without a hickup or defect. It is extremely accurate, even has a side rail for scope rails as a true AK should. I have about 90 rounds of 5.45 silver bear left to go with it. My price is what I paid for it plus the full conversion cost so I'm not making any money off this. If it's too expensive, buy a WASR, they're great guns if you know what to look for but they are just copies and I've had 4 of them, 2 of which had major issues in functionality and reliability (one with a crooked gas block and front sight, the other had a VERY sticky bolt that would lock back at least 5 or 6 times trying to run through one 30 round magazine).

title: For Sale:  Bersa Thunder 9 UC Pro
location: Apex, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
This is my favorite gun for backpacking and day hiking. It gives the the capacity of a much larger gun (13+1, and two mags in this case), the reliability of a hammer all in a compact, non-bulky package. I feel confident that I could defend myself and my family in the woods or in the city with this gun and a magazine full of HP rounds. One of my favorite parts of this gun is the polygonal rifling, which allows me to achieve deadly accurate groups with a compact handgun. I have two identical versions of this gun, and I'm only selling this one because my wife really prefers a revolver when hiking... there's something about the S&W Airlite that her dad gave her that I just can't convince her the wisdom of 9 more rounds, but she likes what she likes. If I could come up with some reason why I needed two I would keep it, but fortunately one of these on my hip is all I need. 

For the sake if clarity, this is a 9mm version. It is also double/single action so it can be fired with or without first cocking the hammer. It has an ambidextrous safety and a small key that can be used to secure the trigger mechanism when stored. If you are planning on using this for home defense I would not recommend using the key when it's in your bedside table, because I wouldn't want to have to fumble around with it in a stressful scenario, but that is of course your decision. 

I am selling hers which is all stock and has less cosmetic wear since she's only carried it once, but we have both shot this one at the range and it probably has about 200 rounds of Hornady HP through it with out any jams. Mine has had that plus a few hundred FMJ  and reloads without a single jam, stovepipe or misfire. The hammer on this has never failed to activate one of my reloaded primers, which I can't say is true for a certain well loved/hated striker fired pistol of mine. All in all this model is my favorite gun to carry because of the hi-cap, small size, accuracy, and hammer fired reliability and I'm really glad that I don't need to sell mine. I'm sure that you will enjoy this gun as much as I do. Thanks for your interest.

Along with giving a 30 day free trial in martial arts, FFA is now giving out FREE gun training courses by certified NRA firearm instructors! This course is designed for NEWBIES.

We will be covering the basics of the different kinds of firearms, how to load, grip, aim, and fire your firearm, how to keep the gun safe in your home, how to clean your gun, and other important safety procedures.
